'''Suwa Gorōnin''' (諏訪御料人, 1530 – December 18, 1555) was a concubine of {{ill|Takeda Shingen|ja|Takeda Shingen|12=draft|12=draft}} (Takeda Harunobu) and the mother of {{ill|Takeda Katsuyori|ja|武田勝頼|12=draft|12=draft}}. She was the daughter of {{ill|Suwa Yorishige|ja|諏訪頼重|12=draft|12=draft}}, the head of the {{ill|Suwa clan|ja|諏訪氏|1=Suwa clan|12=draft|12=draft}}, and his concubine from the {{ill|Omi clan (麻績氏)|ja|小見氏|12=draft|12=draft}} (Omishi). Known also as "Taikata-sama," her actual name remains unknown. In historical sources, she is referred to as "Suwa Gorōnin" or "Suwa Gozen," both terms indicating a noblewoman.
== Biography == Suwa Gorōnin's birth year is uncertain, but according to the ''{{ill|Kōyō Gunkan|ja|甲陽軍鑑|12=draft|12=draft}}'', she became a concubine of Takeda Shingen at age 14 in 1545, suggesting she was born in 1530.<ref name="hira23">{{Cite book|author=平山優|title=長篠合戦と武田勝頼 敗者の日本史9|publisher=吉川弘文館|year=2014|page=23}}</ref><ref name="shiba476">{{Cite book|author=柴辻俊六|title=武田氏家臣団人名辞典|publisher=東京堂出版|year=2015|page=476}}</ref> ''Kōyō Gunkan'' praises her beauty, calling her a "notable beauty."<ref name="shiba476" />
At the time of her father Suwa Yorishige's leadership, the Suwa clan was allied with the {{ill|Takeda clan|ja|武田氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. Yorishige married {{ill|Neene|ja|禰々|12=draft|12=draft}}, Takeda Shingen's half-sister, to strengthen the alliance. However, in 1541, after Shingen ousted his father {{ill|Takeda Nobutora|ja|武田信虎|12=draft|12=draft}}, Yorishige aligned with the {{ill|Uesugi clan|ja|上杉氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, violating the Takeda-Suwa alliance. This led to Takeda's invasion of Suwa, resulting in the fall of the Suwa clan and Yorishige's forced seppuku.
To consolidate his control, Shingen took Suwa Gorōnin as a concubine and planned to have their son, Katsuyori, inherit the Suwa clan's legacy.<ref name="hira23" /> She is believed to have entered the Takeda household around 1545, residing at the {{ill|Tsutsujigasaki Mansion|ja|躑躅ヶ崎館|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="shiba476" />
Suwa Gorōnin died on November 6, 1555. Her grave is located at {{ill|Kenpuku-ji|ja|建福寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in present-day {{ill|Ina, Nagano|ja|伊那市|12=draft|12=draft}}. Her Buddhist name was recorded as "Kenpukuji-dono Baigan Myōkō Daizenni."<ref name="shiba476" /> Another memorial exists at {{ill|Kannon-in (Okaya City)|ja|観音院 (岡谷市)|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Okaya, Nagano|ja|岡谷市|12=draft|12=draft}}, but it was constructed after her death based on fictional accounts.
== Influence and Legacy == According to ''{{ill|Tetsuzan-shū|ja|鉄山集|12=draft|12=draft}}'' and ''Butsugan Zenji Goroku,'' her son Katsuyori performed rituals in her memory, including the 17th death anniversary ceremony in 1571.<ref name="shiba476" />
There is speculation that she was adopted by {{ill|Netsu Motonao|ja|禰津元直|12=draft|12=draft}} to avoid her identity as a former enemy's daughter. This adoption would mean Katsuyori and {{ill|Takeda Nobukiyo|ja|武田信清|12=draft|12=draft}} were both her children, suggesting she lived until the 1560s.
== Cultural Impact == Suwa Gorōnin is often depicted as Takeda Shingen's favorite concubine, although this characterization is debated among historians. Historical dramas and novels have contributed to this portrayal, such as {{ill|Jirō Nitta|ja|新田次郎|12=draft|12=draft}}'s ''{{ill|Takeda Shingen (novel)|ja|Takeda Shingen (小説)|12=draft|12=draft}}'', where she is called "Koi-hime," and {{ill|Yasushi Inoue|ja|井上靖|12=draft|12=draft}}'s ''{{ill|Fūrin Kazan (novel)|ja|風林火山 (小説)|12=draft|12=draft}}'', where she is named "Yūbu-hime."
The annual {{ill|Shingen-kō Festival|ja|信玄公祭り|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kōfu, Yamanashi|ja|甲府市|12=draft|12=draft}} features a "Koi-hime Contest," adding to her legacy in popular culture.
== Depictions in Media == Suwa Gorōnin has been portrayed under various names in films and television dramas: * ''{{ill|Fūrin Kazan (movie)|ja|風林火山 (映画)|12=draft|12=draft}}'' as Yūbu-hime (1969, Toho, actress: {{ill|Yoshiko Sakuma|ja|佐久間良子|12=draft|12=draft}}) * ''{{ill|Takeda Shingen (1988 TV series)|ja|Takeda Shingen (NHK大河ドラマ)|12=draft|12=draft}}'' as Koi-hime (1988, NHK Taiga Drama, actress: {{ill|Yōko Minamino|ja|南野陽子|12=draft|12=draft}}) * ''{{ill|Fūrin Kazan (NHK Taiga Drama)|ja|風林火山 (NHK大河ドラマ)|12=draft|12=draft}}'' as Yūbu-hime (2007, NHK Taiga Drama, actress: {{ill|Kō Shibamoto|ja|柴本幸|12=draft|12=draft}})
== Notes == {{Reflist}}
== References == * {{Cite book|author=Shunroku Shibazutsu|title=武田氏家臣団人名辞典|publisher=Tokyo-dō Publishing|year=2015}} * {{Cite book|author=Masahiro Hirayama|title=長篠合戦と武田勝頼 敗者の日本史9|publisher=Yoshikawa Kōbunkan|year=2014}} * {{Cite book|author=Kazushige Marushima|title=武田氏家臣団人名辞典|publisher=Tokyo-dō Publishing|year=2015}}
== External Links == * [https://www2.nhk.or.jp/archives/movies/?id=D0004180009_00000 Suwa Taisha, Uehara Castle Ruins, and Ryūkōzan Kannon-in: The Hometown of Yūbu-hime] (NHK Archives) ==References== {{reflist}} {{Suwa Faith}}
